comments.body:
Hmm... you're right

Well, unfortunately i'd probably just create the edge type and connection type and name each of the types.  Perhaps in the next version of GraphQL.NET we can change the automatic naming algorithm for connection types.

```cs
public class NewsConnectionType : ConnectionType<AutoRegisteringObjectGraphType<News>, NewsEdgeType>
{
    public NewsConnectionType()
    {
        Name = "NewsConnection";
    }
}

public class NewsEdgeType : EdgeType<AutoRegisteringObjectGraphType<News>>
{
    public NewsEdgeType()
    {
        Name = "NewsEdge";
    }
}

// [OutputType(typeof(NewsConnectionType))]
// or
// [OutputType(typeof(NonNullGraphType<NewsConnectionType>))]
```

An alternate method is to create a concrete type for `News`:

```cs
// note: be sure to end this name in "GraphType"
public class NewsGraphType : AutoRegisteringObjectGraphType<News>
{
}

// [OutputType(typeof(ConnectionType<NewsGraphType>))]
// or
// [OutputType(typeof(NonNullGraphType<ConnectionType<NewsGraphType>>))]

// but will need to be sure the CLR type mapping is registered properly so other references to `News`
// map to the same NewsGraphType
// e.g. .AddClrTypeMappings() during DI configuration
// or this.RegisterTypeMapping<News, NewsGraphType>() during schema configuration
```

You can also register the type mapping for `Connection<News>` so you don't need to use `[OutputType]`

```cs
// in schema constructor, or within ConfigureSchema:
schema.RegisterTypeMapping<Connection<News>, NewsConnectionType>();
// or ConnectionType<News> depending on the solution picked above
```

In this way nullability is automatically determined.

