Hi, 
I want to create a FieldBuilder extension that will be applied after Resolve and conditionally can override Resolve behavior. 
In the example below, the extension is called WithComment. 
it:
- Adds an argument called comment if not already provided.
- In the resolver, it checks if comment is needed (here the logic is only for demo)
- If comment is needed and not provided, it returns response with error.
- if comment is need and also provided, it should fall back to the original resolver execution.

I came up with the following approach and wondering if you can advise if it is correct ot there is any better way.
(Only look at the implementation of WithComment extension)

```csharp
async Task Main()
{
	var schema = new Schema { Query = new TestQuery() };
	var result1 = await schema.ExecuteAsync(_ =>
			{
				_.Query = "{ test1 { status, id, errorMessage } }";
			}
	);

	var result2 = await schema.ExecuteAsync(_ =>
			{
				_.Query = "{ test2 { status, id, errorMessage } }";
			}
	);


	result1.Dump();
	result2.Dump();
}

public class TestQuery : ObjectGraphType
{
	public TestQuery()
	{
		Field<TestResponseType, TestResponse>("test1")
			.Resolve(context =>
			{
				return new TestResponse();
			})
			.WithComment(1);

		Field<TestResponseType, TestResponse>("test2")
			.Resolve(context =>
			{
				return new TestResponse();
			})
			.WithComment(2);

	}
}

public static class FieldBuilderExtensions
{
	public static readonly string COMMENT_ARGUMENT = "comment";

	public static FieldBuilder<TSourceType, TReturnType> WithComment<TSourceType, TReturnType>(
			this FieldBuilder<TSourceType, TReturnType> builder, int value) where TReturnType : BaseResponse, new()
	{
		if (builder.FieldType.Resolver == null) {
			throw new Exception("Resolve must be used before WithComment");
		}
		
		if (builder.FieldType.Arguments == null)
		{
			builder.FieldType.Arguments = new QueryArguments();
		}

		if (!builder.FieldType.Arguments.Any(f => f.Name == COMMENT_ARGUMENT))
		{
			builder.FieldType.Arguments.Add(new QueryArgument<StringGraphType>
			{
				Name = COMMENT_ARGUMENT
			});
		}

		var currentResolver = builder.FieldType.Resolver;

		builder.FieldType.Resolver = new FuncFieldResolver<TSourceType, TReturnType>((IResolveFieldContext<TSourceType> context) =>
		{
			var needsComment = value % 2 == 0;	//Dummy logic here for demo
			var comment = context.GetArgument<string>(COMMENT_ARGUMENT);

			if (needsComment && comment == null)
			{
				return new TReturnType() {
					Status = "Fail",
					ErrorMessage = "Comment must be provided"
				};
			}
			else
			{
				return (TReturnType)currentResolver.ResolveAsync(context).Result;
			}
		});

		return builder;
	}
}

public class TestResponseType : BaseResponseType<TestResponse>
{
	public TestResponseType()
	{
		Field<StringGraphType>("Id");
	}
}

public class BaseResponseType<T> : ObjectGraphType<T>
{
	public BaseResponseType()
	{
		Field<StringGraphType>("status");
		Field<StringGraphType>("errorMessage");
	}
}

public class TestResponse : BaseResponse
{
	public string Id { get; set; }
	public TestResponse()
	{
		Id = "0";
	}
}

public class BaseResponse
{
	public string Status { get; set; } = "success";
	public string ErrorMessage { get; set; } = "";
}
```

comments.body:
I think it looks good.  Here's a couple other ideas also, just FYI:

1. If the comment argument was a non-null argument, validation would fail if the comment was not provided, so you might not need to overwrite the field resolver.  Validation has a benefit that the query does not execute if validation fails.  In your example above, you indicated that the comment was only conditionally required based on runtime logic, so this might not work for you.

Also, it seems that you are returning error messages within the GraphQL response.  I would personally recommend using GraphQL errors instead, and unify error responses with validation errors.

2. If the comment is not used in the resolver but is simply there for logging, you could likely provide it "out of bounds" as a directive or comment, and write a validation rule that ensures that the directive or comment exists.  So for example it is possible to validate this within a validation rule:

```gql
{
  something {
    # a comment here <-- validation code ensures there is a comment here prior to execution of 'child' below
    child { id }
  }
}
```

However, the example above probably violates spec as comments should be treated as whitespace during execution.

> you could likely provide it "out of bounds" as a directive or comment

Of course directive  can help here

```graphql
{
  something {
    child @comment("Hello world!") { id }
  }
}
```
Directive looks more promising, structured (unlike comments). You **may** go this way but prepare to fight with some difficulties - exposing directives via introspection, using GraphQL clients that aware of directives, write validation rule checking directive. The official specification has not yet been able to fully reveal all the possibilities of directives.

Mutation:
```graphql
mutation {
  module {
    setUserName(name: "KeithsModule") @performQuery {
      result {
        code
      }
    }
  }
}
```
Imagining this mutation affected "userName", "userDescription", and "catalogNumber", the mutation would (using a DI suggestQuery service) specify "{ module { userName userDescription } module { catalogNumber } }" as the "suggestedQuery". 
 The @performQuery directive would signal the server to retrieve the suggestedQuery (via the serviceProvider) insert the query into the executing document.

the client enters the following mutation:
```gql
mutation {
    module {
        setUserName(name: "KeithsModule") @performSuggestedQuery {
            result {
                code
            }
        }
    }
}
```

in addition to resolving the mutation and returning the mutation's response result code, the resolver inserts into the mutation's response the suggested query:
```gql
{
    module {
        userName userDescription
    }
    module {
        catalogNumber
    }
}
```
the graphql response to the mutation would be:
```json
{
  "data": {
    "module": {
      "setUserName": {
        "result": {
          "code": 0
        },
        "suggestedQuery": {
          "module": {
            "userName": "KeithsModule",
            "userDescription": "Keiths Module Description",
            "catalogNumber": "2198-EW"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Rather than a directive, have you considered this instead:

```gql
mutation {
    module {
        setUserName(name: "KeithsModule") {
            result {
                code
            }
            suggestedQuery
        }
    }
}
```

Then `suggestedQuery` is a `JsonScalarType` or similar (a custom scalar graph type), which is a legal GraphQL scalar which returns structured data in the format you described:

```json
{
  "data": {
    "module": {
      "setUserName": {
        "result": {
          "code": 0
        },
        "suggestedQuery": {
          "module": {
            "userName": "KeithsModule",
            "userDescription": "Keiths Module Description",
            "catalogNumber": "2198-EW"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

The above could be implemented by having the `suggestedQuery` field call another GraphQL call internally to execute whatever suggested query was dictated by your DI-injected service.  You can use `.ToValue()` or similar to convert the internal GraphQL response back into a dictionary to return from the `suggestedQuery` resolver.  You will need to consider what happens if the internal execution returns an error, of course -- perhaps just returning null is sufficient.

Now, all of this assumes that the caller will know what the format of the suggested query would be.  Which begs the question: if the caller knows what the suggested query is, why doesn't the schema know what it is and assign the correct GraphQL type to the field?  I'll assume you have a good answer for this question, and offer a suggestion as a solution: include the suggested query text in the response, as shown below:

```gql
mutation {
    module {
        setUserName(name: "KeithsModule") {
            result {
                code
            }
            suggestedQuery
            suggestedQueryResponse
        }
    }
}
```

which returns:

```json
{
  "data": {
    "module": {
      "setUserName": {
        "result": {
          "code": 0
        },
        "suggestedQuery": "{ module { userName userDescription } module { catalogNumber } }",
        "suggestedQueryResponse": {
          "module": {
            "userName": "KeithsModule",
            "userDescription": "Keiths Module Description",
            "catalogNumber": "2198-EW"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Now I wouldn't want callers to have to parse the `suggestedQuery` field to decipher the `suggestedQueryResponse` field, but I guess it is possible to do so.

Here are some other things I've done in the past which you may be able to pull ideas from:

1. The GraphQL type of the `setUserName` mutation is the `ModuleType` so that any property from the updated module can be returned

```gql
mutation {
    module {
        setUserName(name: "KeithsModule") {
            userName
            userDescription
            catalogNumber
            # any other fields of the updated module can be selected here
        }
    }
}
```

2. Add a `query` field to the root of the `MutationType` which points to `QueryType` so that any query can be run in conjunction with the mutation.  These queries could execute within the same SQL transaction as the mutation, for example.  And since according to GraphQL spec, mutations execute serially, the caller can define if the query can run before or after the mutation:

```gql
mutation {
    module {
        setUserName(name: "KeithsModule") {
            result { code }
        }
    }
    query {
        module(name: "KeithsModule") {
            userName
            userDescription
            catalogNumber
        }
    }
}
```

Since GraphQL spec allows querying the same field multiple times via aliases, it is even possible to return any arbitrary data from both before and after the mutation, like this:

```gql
mutation {
    queryBefore: query {
        module(name: "KeithsModule") {
            userName
            userDescription
            catalogNumber
        }
    }
    module {
        setUserName(name: "KeithsModule") {
            result { code }
        }
    }
    queryAfter: query {
        module(name: "KeithsModule") {
            userName
            userDescription
            catalogNumber
        }
    }
}
```

I think your idea about the form of the mutation is better than the directive idea I had...certainly more straightforward.  As in:
```gql
mutation {
    module {
        setUserName(name: "KeithsModule") {
            result {
                code
            }
            suggestedQuery
            suggestedQueryResponse
        }
    }
}
```
In one of your responses, you stated 
>The above could be implemented by having the suggestedQuery field call another GraphQL call internally to execute whatever suggested query was dictated...

Would you mind providing an example on how to do that?

Also, you mentioned that in this case, the `suggestedQueryResponse` could be a `JsonScalarType` which allows structured json like that returned by the server.  I looked up #474 and saw references to a `AnyScalarGraphType`, but I could not find anything in the repo on `JsonScalarType`.  Would you elaborate a little more on this?

One other thing, you asked if the caller would understand the format of the `suggestedQueryResponse` json.  I'm thinking that since this field contains a response to a valid GraphQL query, which conforms to an existing schema, then the caller would be able to process that field with the same code with which it would process the actual query response (had the caller actually sent the query).

Well since I already am half done answering it...something like this:

```cs
public async Task<object?> ExecuteSubquery(IResolveFieldContext context, string suggestedQuery)
{
    try {
        var executer = context.RequestServices.GetRequiredService<IDocumentExecuter<ISchema>>();
        var result = await executer.ExecuteAsync(new ExecutionOptions {
            Query = suggestedQuery,
            RequestedServices = context.RequestServices,
            User = context.User,
            CancellationToken = context.CancellationToken,
            //Root = root,
        });
        if (!result.Executed || result.Data == null || result.Errors != null)
            return null;
        return ((ExecutionNode)result.Data).ToValue();
    } catch {
        return null;
    }
}
```

I did some extra research and noticed that one can use the GetArgument extension method:

```
var take = context.GetArgument<int>("Take");
if (take > 0)
{
    pageableQuery.Take = take;
}
```

