}
```

with this code:
```
var sortOrderArgDef = ctx.FieldDefinition.Arguments?.FirstOrDefault(arg => arg.Name == "sortOrder");
var sortInputType = sortOrderArgDef?.ResolvedType as InputObjectGraphType;

var arg = ctx.FieldAst.Arguments.FirstOrDefault(a => a.Name == "sortOrder");
if (arg is object && sortInputType is object)
{ 
   foreach(ObjectValue child in arg.Children)
   {
      foreach(ObjectField field in child.ObjectFields)
      {
         // handle it here
      }
   }
}
```
This is exactly what I was looking for. Works like a charm.

For the sake of reference, since others might read this looking for a similar solution, I decided to go with the following solution to be both backward compatible and support multiple sort order fields at the same time.

```
{
   users(sortOrder : {
         name : DESC
         _thenBy : {
            registrationDate : ASC
            _thenBy : {
               id : DESC
            }
         }})
   {
      totalCount
      items {
         id
         name         
      }
   }
}
```

The resolved type of the `_thenBy` field is the type of the `sortOrder` field, so this goes recursively as much as needed. And it's pretty easy to parse it, It also works with variables:

```
{
  "order" :{
      "name" : "DESC",
      "_thenBy" : {
        "registrationDate" :"ASC",
        "_thenBy" : {
          "id" :"DESC"
        }}}
}
```

