There's another way you can implement your schema that would probably work much better: use a batch data loader to group up a number of requests and return them to each of the field resolvers.  Here's how I would set it up:

1. Create a dummy interface and classes containing the request parameters each type of query.

```cs
public interface IRequest
{
}

public class ContentRequest : IRequest
{
    public int ClientId { get; set; }
    public List<Filter> Filters { get; set; }
    public string ClientKey { get; set; }
}

public class FindRequest : IRequest
{
    public string QueryString { get; set; }
    // other query parameters
}

public class ItemListingsRequest : IRequest
{
    // see above
}
```

2. Create a custom data loader where the key is the dummy interface, and it returns an object.  The "data loader" can group all of the requests together server-side and respond with data for each of them.  Be sure caching is turned off.

```cs
public class MyDataRequestor : DataLoaderBase<IRequest, object>
{
    private readonly IDataService _dataService; // <-- example service

    public MyDataRequestor(IDataService dataService) : base(false)  // no caching
    {
        // pull DI services as necessary here
        _dataService = dataService;
    }

    protected override async Task FetchAsync(IEnumerable<DataLoaderPair<IRequest, object>> list, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        // process all of the requests, calling SetResult on each of the pairs
        // below is a simplified example that executes the requests sequentially, but you can change this as desired
        foreach (var pair in list)
        {
            pair.SetResult(pair.Key switch
                {
                    // if the request is a ContentRequest, return a List<ContentResponse>
                    ContentRequest contentRequest => await _dataService.ProcessContentRequestAsync(contentRequest, cancellationToken),

                    FindRequest findRequest => await _dataService.ProcessFindRequestAsync(findRequest, cancellationToken),

                    ItemListingsRequest itemListingsRequest => await _dataService.ProcessItemListingsRequestAsync(itemListingsRequest, cancellationToken),

                    _ => throw new NotSupportedException()
                });
        }
    }
}
```

3. Register the data loader in your DI container as a singleton or scoped, depending on your needs.  If you are going to register it as a singleton, be sure that data loader caching is turned off, or else it will eventually use all of the memory on your server as there is no technique to clear the cache.  Caching won't be useful anyway because without `Equals` being implemented on the class, none of the `IRequest` objects will equal each other.  (It is something that could be implemented, however.)

4. Call the data loader from the `contentRequest`, `find`, and `itemListings` field resolvers.  If the data loader is registered as a singleton, you can include a reference in the graph type constructor.  If not, you will need to obtain a reference from `context.RequestServices`.  I am going to assume it is scoped in the below example.

```cs
public class TitanQuery : ObjectGraphType<object>
{
    public TitanQuery(....)
    {
        Name = "Query";

        FieldAsync<ListGraphType<ContentResponseType>>(
            "contentRequest",
            arguments: new QueryArguments(
                    new QueryArgument<NonNullGraphType<IntGraphType>>
                    {
                        Name = "clientId",
                        Description = "Client Id of the request"

                    },
                    new QueryArgument<ListGraphType<FilterType>>
                    {
                        Name = "filters",
                        Description = "Filters"
                    },
                    new QueryArgument<StringGraphType>
                    {
                        Name = "clientKey",
                        DefaultValue = "abc",
                        Description = "some stuff"
                    }
                ),

            resolve: async context =>
            {
                var dataLoader = context.RequestServices.GetRequiredService<MyDataRequestor>();
                var request = new ContentRequest {
                    ClientId = context.GetArgument<int>("clientId"),
                    Filters = context.GetArgument<List<Filter>>("filters"),
                    ClientKey = context.GetArgument<string>("clientKey"),
                };

                // after being processed by the dataloader, will return a List<ContentResponse>
                return dataLoader.LoadAsync(request);
            }
        );
    }
}
```

FYI, how data loaders work is that they will execute all nodes possible until none remain that can be executed.  Then it will execute/trigger all pending data loader nodes at once.  See `SerialExecutionStrategy` and `ParallelExecutionStrategy` source code for specifics.

Also, I'd be real careful about registering the data loader as a singleton.  Specifically, let's say two request come in at the same time like this:

```gql
# request A

query {
  contentRequest { ... }
}

# request B

query {
  contentRequest { ... }
  find { ... }
}
```

Then what can happen is that the two `contentRequest` queries can get grouped into the same dataloader call, while the second half of request B (the `find` query) gets put into a separate call.  Worse yet, the first group of requests gets called from the context of request A, so if there is any code that relies on `IHttpContextAccessor`, it will return the wrong http context for the second content request. Similar issues can occur with any async-local data.  I had these problems in one of my live environments; it was very hard to track down since the probability of it happening is rare.  Now if that is perfectly fine (no issues with authentication or anything else), then sure, I guess...  But also if the `FetchAsync` code in the data loader depends on any scoped services, you'll need the data loader to be a scoped service.

I think this solution should work well for you.  It also can fully handle any valid graphql query, whether it uses aliases, fragments, etc.

