Yes, but you can change the code in FetchAsync however you want. For example:

```cs
    protected override async Task FetchAsync(IEnumerable<DataLoaderPair<IRequest, object>> list, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        //1. find the different types of requests, and ensure that only max of one is requested for each type
        //  (because according to graphql spec there could be multiple of a single one)
        var contentRequestPair = list.SingleOrDefault(x => x.Key is ContentRequest);
        var contentRequest = (ContentRequest)contentRequestPair?.Key;
        //ditto for findRequest and itemListingsRequest

        //2. pull the common variables
        var clientId = contentRequest?.ClientId ?? findRequest?.ClientId ?? itemListingsRequest?.ClientId;
        //ditto for filters and clientkey

        //optional: throw an exception if clientId is different for contentRequest vs findRequest vs itemListingsRequest, or similar logic

        //3. initialize the process request
        var request = new ProcessRequest {
            //common properties
            ClientId = clientId,
            ClientKey = clientKey,
            Filters = filters,
            //properties specific to the type of request
            QueryString = findRequest?.Find,
            ...
        };

        // 4. todo: execute your request (async or sync)
        var processResponse = await ExecuteProcessRequestAsync(processRequest, cancellationToken);

        // 5. set the results
        if (contentRequestPair != null)
        {
            // create the data model for the graph
            var contentResponse = processResponse.whatever;
            // set the answer
            contentRequestPair.SetResult(contentResponse);
        }
        listRequestPair?.SetResult(processResponse.answer2);
        // ditto for the other objects
    }
```

Some more idea: group the `list` variable by the common properties, so e.g. if there are different clientIds specified it will execute separate requests rather than execute one of the two with the wrong clientid.  Apply similar logic if there are multiple `contentRequest`s queried, so it will execute separate requests rather than throwing an error during `SingleOrDefault`.

