I think I understood your question.

>  it would grab the first character and try to capitalize it. The first character is '_'

First, you confuse the parent field and the child field. The converter converts the names of child fields, for example `types`, `args`. However, the current code indeed can be simplified because all introspection fields are lowercase:
```c#
public class PascalCaseFieldNameConverter : IFieldNameConverter
    {
        private static readonly Type[] IntrospectionTypes = { typeof(SchemaIntrospection) };

        public static readonly PascalCaseFieldNameConverter Instance = new PascalCaseFieldNameConverter();

        public string NameFor(string field, Type parentType) => isIntrospectionType(parentType) ? field : field.ToPascalCase();

        private bool isIntrospectionType(Type type) => IntrospectionTypes.Contains(type);
    }
```

and

```c#
 public class DefaultFieldNameConverter : IFieldNameConverter
    {
        public static readonly DefaultFieldNameConverter Instance = new DefaultFieldNameConverter();

        public string NameFor(string field, Type parentType) => field;
    }
```

I think I found my answer.  The `GraphTypesLookup` constructor runs before the `GraphTypesLookup.FieldNameConverter` property is set, so all the introspection fields always get configured with the `CamelCaseNameConverter` (the default value of `GraphTypesLookup.FieldNameConverter`), no matter how `Schema.FieldNameConverter` or `ExecutionOptions.FieldNameConverter` is set.

I've proven this by three steps:
1. Change CamelCaseFieldNameConverter.cs to the following:
``` C#
using System;
using System.Linq;
using GraphQL.Introspection;

namespace GraphQL.Conversion
{
    public class CamelCaseFieldNameConverterOld : IFieldNameConverter
    {
        public static readonly CamelCaseFieldNameConverterOld Instance = new CamelCaseFieldNameConverterOld();

        public string NameFor(string field, Type parentType) => field.ToCamelCase();
    }
    public class CamelCaseFieldNameConverter : IFieldNameConverter
    {
        private static readonly Type[] IntrospectionTypes = { typeof(SchemaIntrospection) };

        public static readonly CamelCaseFieldNameConverter Instance = new CamelCaseFieldNameConverter();

        public string NameFor(string field, Type parentType)
        {
            if (isIntrospectionType(parentType) && field != "__schema" && field != "__type" && field != "__typename")
                throw new Exception();
            return field.ToCamelCase();
        }

        private bool isIntrospectionType(Type type) => IntrospectionTypes.Contains(type);
    }
}
```
2. Change the GraphTypesLookup constructor to set `FieldNameConverter` to `CamelCaseFieldNameConverterOld.Instance` at the start of the function, and back to the default of `CamelCaseFieldNameConverter.Instance` at the end of the function
3. Run all tests -- which all pass showing that no exception is thrown

